// Parameter-consume analysis (Concept C — the argument-side dual of
// `ReturnBorrowAnalysis`, and the structural replacement for the refcount
// inserter's hand-synced callee allowlists).
//
// A function CONSUMES parameter P when it takes ownership of P's reference: it
// MOVES P's `+1` into durable storage WITHOUT increfing — a container's element
// buffer (`__managed_mem_set`), a list node (`mrt_managed_list_*_value`), a heap
// struct field, or the wrapper struct it RETURNS (`Array.init`'s
// `return Self{managed: arg}`). A consuming parameter's caller must NOT release its
// argument at the call's last use: the `+1` transferred to the callee's container,
// balanced by that container's destructor. The OPPOSITE — a BORROW — reads P
// without taking its reference (`Map.get`/`Set.contains` probe the same
// type-parameter key but only compare it); the caller keeps ownership and releases.
//
// This was previously approximated by THREE hand-maintained callee-NAME allowlists
// in InsertRefcounts.maxon (`isConsumingContainerMutator`, `calleeMovesValue`,
// `calleeTransparentlyWrapsArg`) — every new stdlib container method a latent
// double-free (missed move) or leak (over-suppression) until someone edited a
// string. Identifying callees by name is fragile and wrong; this pass computes the
// fact STRUCTURALLY from each callee's body instead (the consume-side of the
// move-model rewrite — "Concept C": derive per-param consume bits from the body).
//
// WHY A PRE-INSERTION STRUCTURAL WALK IS SOUND. This pass runs AFTER
// `lowerMaxonToStd` + inlining/DCE and BEFORE `insertRefcounts` (the SOLE incref
// placer). So every body it sees has ZERO refcount ops yet: every `store_indirect`
// of a parameter is a RAW move (no retain-then-store to disambiguate). "P flows to a
// store/box/consuming-call sink" therefore IS "P is consumed" — no incref-tracking
// needed, exactly as `ReturnBorrowAnalysis` reasons.
//
// THE LEAF RULE. A function consumes its parameter `i` iff, within its body, the
// SSA value of `param i` (or an SSA copy reached through pass-through forwarding —
// loads/arith that re-derive the SAME managed pointer) reaches a CONSUME SINK:
//   - a `store_indirect` / `box_value` of it into heap storage (the durable-store
//     leaf: `__managed_mem_set`'s raw store, a `Self{field: P}` wrapper store), OR
//   - an argument at position `j` of a call to a function G that CONSUMES param `j`
//     (the forwarding edge: `Array.push` → `managed.set` → `__managed_mem_set`).
// It is NOT consumed when P only reaches loads / comparisons / returns-as-borrow.
//
// The forwarding edge makes this a FIXPOINT over the module's call graph, monotonic
// (a consume bit, once set, stays set), terminating in <= (#functions x #params)
// rounds. It bottoms out at the INTRINSIC LEAF-CONSUMERS — a tiny set of raw runtime
// helpers (`mrt_managed_list_*`) whose bodies live in runtime.std (slot-form, linked
// at the backend, never in this module) and so cannot be analyzed structurally.
// These are compiler-internal primitives, NOT user-facing API that grows, so seeding
// them is legitimate — it is the high-level container-method list (which grew with
// every stdlib method) that the structural walk eliminates.
//
// RETURN-SIDE COMPANION (`funcReturnsConsumedArg`). A transparent wrapper
// (`Array.init`/`Vector.init`: `return Self{managed: arg}`) both CONSUMES arg 0 AND
// RETURNS a value owning arg 0's `+1` (the result aliases the arg's storage with no
// fresh alloc/incref). The consume bit covers the arg side; this pass ALSO records
// the return-side fact so the inserter treats such a result as already-owning a
// transferable `+1` — kept DISTINCT from the per-class `plusOneOwnership` per the
// design (it is about a call RESULT inheriting its wrapped arg's reference).

// Run the analysis: populate `project.funcParamConsumes` (per-function per-parameter
// consume bits) and `project.funcReturnsConsumedArg` (transparent-wrapper results) to
// a fixpoint over `module`'s forwarding edges. Returns the module unchanged (mutates
// only the two `project` registries — no IR is rewritten).
//
// CACHE INTERACTION. The STDLIB consume facts are computed ONCE when the stdlib cache
// is built (this pass runs over the full stdlib module during cache warming) and
// PERSISTED in the cache (`captureRegistries`/`restoreRegistries` in StdlibCache.maxon),
// restored into `project.funcParamConsumes`/`funcReturnsConsumedArg` before the user
// build. So on a user build the stdlib facts are ALREADY present in `project` when this
// pass runs; the fixpoint here only ADDS the USER functions' consume facts (a user
// `wrapper(box)` that forwards `box` into a consuming stdlib callee), forwarding from
// the restored stdlib bits. A non-inlined consuming stdlib callee (`Array.push` linked,
// not inlined) is a signature-only stub in the user module but its consume bit was
// restored from the cache, so the user caller reads the real bit. The intrinsic-leaf
// seed is re-applied every run (cheap, idempotent) so the leaves are present even on a
// fresh/cache-bypass build.
export function analyzeParamConsumes(module StdModule, project Project) returns StdModule
	seedIntrinsicLeafConsumers(project)

	// Structural "may return this arg" relation, computed ONCE before the consume
	// fixpoint (it depends only on each body's return terminators, not on consume bits).
	// `funcMayReturnArg[callee]` flags each parameter position the callee RETURNS on
	// SOME path — the IDENTITY-PASSTHROUGH shape (`return param`, e.g.
	// `FilePath.resolveFileURL`/`normalizeSeparators` returning their input unchanged on
	// the no-op branch). The result of such a call ALIASES the passed argument, so the
	// consume walk must follow the call's result as another handle on the parameter.
	// Without this a param laundered through a passthrough call before reaching a
	// `Self{field: …}` store-sink is missed → the wrapper's consume bit is unset → the
	// caller DROPS the arg even though the wrapper kept it (the `FilePath from "x"`
	// global UAF). Computed where bodies are present (stdlib build); the consume bits it
	// produces are cached, so the user build needs no separate persistence.
	let mayReturnArg = computeMayReturnArgMap(module)

	// Fixpoint: recompute each function's consume bits until no bit flips. Each round
	// consults the callees' CURRENT bits (the restored stdlib facts + this round's), so
	// a consume fact propagates one forwarding hop per round; monotonic, so it settles.
	var changed = true
	while changed 'fixpoint'
		changed = false
		for funcIdx in 0 upto module.functions.count() 'eachFunc'
			let func = try module.functions.get(funcIdx) otherwise panic("analyzeParamConsumes: functions.get OOB at {funcIdx}")
			if func.blockRefs.count() == 0 'empty'
				continue
			end 'empty'
			if updateFuncConsumeBits(module, func: func, project: project, mayReturnArg: mayReturnArg) 'flipped'
				changed = true
			end 'flipped'
		end 'eachFunc'
	end 'fixpoint'

	logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-PCA-DONE funcs={module.functions.count()} consumingCallees={project.funcParamConsumes.count()} wrappers={project.funcReturnsConsumedArg.count()}")

	// With the consume facts settled, correct every `__gt_spawn` managed_mask:
	// the GT trampoline drops the spawn-time reference of each mask-bit arg
	// after the spawned function returns (it is the arg's CALLING FRAME), but
	// a spawned callee that CONSUMES a param already spent that reference —
	// the trampoline's drop would over-release it (the subprocess-async
	// `Configuration`-builder over-free). The mask is emitted at lowering,
	// BEFORE these bits exist for user callees, so the correction lives here.
	adjustGtSpawnMasks(module, project: project)

	return module
end 'analyzeParamConsumes'

// Rewrite each `__gt_spawn(funcRef F, count, buf)` site's managed_mask store
// (`store [buf+8] = mask`) to `mask and not consumedBits(F)`. The mask const
// may be CSE-shared with unrelated constants (cse runs before this pass), so
// the store is repointed at a FRESH const op rather than mutating the old one
// (DCE collects it if orphaned).
function adjustGtSpawnMasks(module StdModule, project Project)
	for func in module.functions 'eachFunc'
		var maskIdRef = NoValueIdRef
		for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
			let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("adjustGtSpawnMasks: blockRef not in module.blocks")
			maskIdRef = adjustGtSpawnMasksInBlock(module, func: func, block: block, project: project, idRef: maskIdRef)
		end 'eachBlock'
	end 'eachFunc'
end 'adjustGtSpawnMasks'

// Sentinel "no ValueIdRef minted yet for this function" — the fresh-id scan is
// deferred until a block actually contains a spawn whose mask needs clearing.
let NoValueIdRef = 0

function adjustGtSpawnMasksInBlock(module StdModule, func IrFunction, block IrBlock, project Project, idRef ValueIdRefHandle) returns ValueIdRefHandle
	var liveIdRef = idRef
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("adjustGtSpawnMasksInBlock: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let (isSpawn, funcValueId, bufValueId) = gtSpawnOperandsOf(op)
		if not isSpawn 'notSpawn'
			continue
		end 'notSpawn'
		let calleeName = funcRefTargetInBlock(module, block: block, valueId: funcValueId)
		if calleeName.isEmpty() 'noStaticCallee'
			continue
		end 'noStaticCallee'
		let consumedMask = consumedArgMaskOf(project, callee: calleeName)
		if consumedMask == 0 'nothingConsumed'
			continue
		end 'nothingConsumed'
		liveIdRef = repointSpawnMaskStore(module, func: func, block: block, bufValueId: bufValueId, clearBits: consumedMask, idRef: liveIdRef)
	end 'eachOp'
	return liveIdRef
end 'adjustGtSpawnMasksInBlock'

// The (present, funcRefValueId, argBufValueId) triple of a direct
// `__gt_spawn(func_ptr, count, arg_buf)` call op.
function gtSpawnOperandsOf(op StdOp) returns (bool, ValueId, ValueId)
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives gtSpawnCallOperandsOf(c)
		arith gives (false, 0, 0)
		control gives (false, 0, 0)
		memory gives (false, 0, 0)
		system gives (false, 0, 0)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'gtSpawnOperandsOf'

function gtSpawnCallOperandsOf(c StdCallOp) returns (bool, ValueId, ValueId)
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives gtSpawnArgIdsOf(callee, argIds: argIds)
		ret gives (false, 0, 0)
		tryCall to errorReturn gives (false, 0, 0)
	end 'check'
end 'gtSpawnCallOperandsOf'

function gtSpawnArgIdsOf(callee String, argIds ValueIdArray) returns (bool, ValueId, ValueId)
	if callee != "__gt_spawn" or argIds.count() != 3 'notSpawn'
		return (false, 0, 0)
	end 'notSpawn'
	let funcValueId = try argIds.get(0) otherwise panic("gtSpawnArgIdsOf: argIds.get(0) failed despite count==3")
	let bufValueId = try argIds.get(2) otherwise panic("gtSpawnArgIdsOf: argIds.get(2) failed despite count==3")
	return (true, funcValueId, bufValueId)
end 'gtSpawnArgIdsOf'

// The funcRef target name defining `valueId` within `block`, or "" when the
// definition isn't a same-block funcRef (lowerAsyncCallReal always emits the
// funcRef contiguously with the spawn, and the inliner splices bodies whole,
// so a miss means an unexpected shape — skipped conservatively).
function funcRefTargetInBlock(module StdModule, block IrBlock, valueId ValueId) returns String
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("funcRefTargetInBlock: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let name = funcRefTargetOf(op, valueId: valueId)
		if not name.isEmpty() 'hit'
			return name
		end 'hit'
	end 'eachOp'
	return ""
end 'funcRefTargetInBlock'

function funcRefTargetOf(op StdOp, valueId ValueId) returns String
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives funcRefCallTargetOf(c, valueId: valueId)
		arith gives ""
		control gives ""
		memory gives ""
		system gives ""
	end 'dispatch'
end 'funcRefTargetOf'

function funcRefCallTargetOf(c StdCallOp, valueId ValueId) returns String
	return match c 'check'
		funcRef(resultId, funcName) gives(funcName if resultId == valueId else "")
		ret gives ""
		call gives ""
		tryCall to witnessTryCall gives ""
		tailCall to errorReturn gives ""
	end 'check'
end 'funcRefCallTargetOf'

// Pack `callee`'s consume bits into a trampoline-shaped mask (bit i = param i,
// capped at the trampoline's 7-arg window like the lowering's mask scan).
function consumedArgMaskOf(project Project, callee String) returns MachineWord
	let bits = try project.funcParamConsumes.get(callee) otherwise return 0
	var mask = 0 as MachineWord
	var limit = bits.count()
	if limit > 7 'cap'
		limit = 7
	end 'cap'
	for i in 0 upto limit 'each'
		if (try bits.get(i) otherwise false) 'set'
			mask = mask or (1 shl (i as ParsedInt))
		end 'set'
	end 'each'
	return mask
end 'consumedArgMaskOf'

typealias ValueIdRefHandle = int(0 to u64.max)

// Repoint the `store [bufValueId + 8] = mask` op at a fresh const carrying
// `mask and not clearBits`. Returns the (possibly just-minted) running max
// value id so multiple spawns in one function keep ids unique.
function repointSpawnMaskStore(module StdModule, func IrFunction, block IrBlock, bufValueId ValueId, clearBits MachineWord, idRef ValueIdRefHandle) returns ValueIdRefHandle
	for pos in 0 upto block.opRefs.count() 'eachOp'
		let opIdx = try block.opRefs.get(pos) otherwise panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: opRefs.get OOB at {pos}")
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let maskValueId = maskStoreValueOf(op, bufValueId: bufValueId)
		if maskValueId == 0 'notMaskStore'
			continue
		end 'notMaskStore'
		let (haveMask, oldMask) = constValueInBlock(module, block: block, valueId: maskValueId)
		if not haveMask 'noConst'
			panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: __gt_spawn mask store's value %{maskValueId} is not a same-block const")
		end 'noConst'
		let newMask = oldMask and not clearBits
		if newMask == oldMask 'unchanged'
			return idRef
		end 'unchanged'
		var nextId = idRef
		if nextId == NoValueIdRef 'mintRef'
			nextId = scanMaxValueId(func, module: module) + 1
		end 'mintRef'
		let newConstId = nextId as ValueId
		let constOpIdx = module.ops.count()
		module.ops.push(StdOp.arith(StdArithOp.const(StdArithConst.create(StdArithConstOpcode.constI64, resultId: newConstId, value: newMask as IntConstant))))
		try block.opRefs.insert(pos, value: constOpIdx) otherwise panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: opRefs.insert failed at {pos}")
		// The store shifted to pos+1; rewrite it to consume the fresh const.
		let storeOpIdx = try block.opRefs.get(pos + 1) otherwise panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: opRefs.get OOB after insert")
		try module.ops.set(storeOpIdx, value: StdOp.system(StdSystemOp.storeIndirect(bufValueId, offset: 8, valueId: newConstId, width: StoreWidth.qword, isFloat: false))) otherwise panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: ops.set OOB at {storeOpIdx}")
		return (nextId + 1) as ValueIdRefHandle
	end 'eachOp'
	panic("repointSpawnMaskStore: no `store [buf+8]` mask store found for __gt_spawn buffer %{bufValueId}")
end 'repointSpawnMaskStore'

// The stored value id when `op` is the spawn buffer's mask store
// (`store_indirect [bufValueId + 8] = v`), else 0.
function maskStoreValueOf(op StdOp, bufValueId ValueId) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysMaskStoreValueOf(s, bufValueId: bufValueId)
		arith gives 0
		control gives 0
		call gives 0
		memory gives 0
	end 'dispatch'
end 'maskStoreValueOf'

function sysMaskStoreValueOf(s StdSystemOp, bufValueId ValueId) returns ValueId
	return match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(addrId, offset, valueId, _, _) gives(valueId if (addrId == bufValueId and offset == 8) else 0)
		loadIndirect gives 0
		globalAddr to loadByte gives 0
		osExit to osWrite gives 0
		free gives 0
		osWriteErr to loadFramePtr gives 0
		funcAddr gives 0
		drop gives 0
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives 0
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives 0
		boxValue to dropTypeParam gives 0
	end 'check'
end 'sysMaskStoreValueOf'

// The (present, value) of a same-block `constI64` defining `valueId`.
function constValueInBlock(module StdModule, block IrBlock, valueId ValueId) returns (bool, MachineWord)
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("constValueInBlock: opIdx not in module.ops")
		let (hit, value) = constValueOf(op, valueId: valueId)
		if hit 'found'
			return (true, value)
		end 'found'
	end 'eachOp'
	return (false, 0)
end 'constValueInBlock'

function constValueOf(op StdOp, valueId ValueId) returns (bool, MachineWord)
	return match op 'dispatch'
		arith(a) gives arithConstValueOf(a, valueId: valueId)
		call gives (false, 0)
		control gives (false, 0)
		memory gives (false, 0)
		system gives (false, 0)
	end 'dispatch'
end 'constValueOf'

function arithConstValueOf(a StdArithOp, valueId ValueId) returns (bool, MachineWord)
	return match a 'check'
		const(c) gives((c.resultId == valueId, c.value as MachineWord))
		unary gives (false, 0)
		binary gives (false, 0)
	end 'check'
end 'arithConstValueOf'

// Recompute `func`'s consume bits this round; return true iff any bit newly flipped
// to true (drives the fixpoint). Reads callees' CURRENT bits for forwarding.
function updateFuncConsumeBits(module StdModule, func IrFunction, project Project, mayReturnArg MayReturnArgMap) returns bool
	let paramValues = collectParamValues(module, func: func)
	var prior = try project.funcParamConsumes.get(func.name) otherwise BoolArray.create()
	var flipped = false

	for paramIndex in 0 upto func.paramCount 'eachParam'
		if boolArrayGet(prior, idx: paramIndex) 'alreadyConsumed'
			continue
		end 'alreadyConsumed'
		let paramVal = paramValueForIndex(paramValues, paramIndex: paramIndex)
		if paramVal == CONSUME_NO_VALUE 'noSsaValue'
			continue
		end 'noSsaValue'
		// NOTE on precision: a non-managed param (an `__mm_alloc` size/tag, a slab raw
		// address) can reach a store-sink too, but the inserter NEVER treats a
		// non-managed value as a release candidate, so a spurious consume bit on it is
		// inert. We deliberately do NOT gate on `func.isValueManaged(paramVal)` here:
		// the managed/type-param classification is not reliably populated on stdlib
		// TEMPLATE bodies at cache-warming time (the generic `Array.push`/`Map.insert`
		// element params would be skipped), which would zero out the real consume set.
		// The dangerous case to exclude is a RETAIN (a managed borrow-capture), handled
		// by the incref gate below.
		//
		// A param the function INCREFS is RETAINED, not consumed: the function took
		// its OWN reference (the caller still owns theirs), so the caller must still
		// release at the call. The canonical case is `__ManagedMemoryCursor`'s
		// `lowerCreateCursor`, which manually increfs `source` before storing it into
		// the cursor (the cursor's destructor drops that retained ref) — so
		// `ArrayIterator.create`/`createCursor` borrow-capture their source rather
		// than consuming it. Excluding incref'd params is what distinguishes a
		// retain-then-store (borrow) from a raw move-store (consume); both otherwise
		// look identical pre-insertion (`Array.init`'s `Self{managed: arg}` vs the
		// cursor's `Self{raw: cursor}` over a retained source).
		if functionIncrefsValue(module, func: func, valueId: paramVal) 'retained'
			continue
		end 'retained'
		// A TYPE-PARAMETER-typed parameter is consumed BY CONVENTION: the callee
		// owns its generic-typed params (`releaseKindAtLastUse`'s type-param domain
		// drops them at last use — the legacy injector contract), so ownership
		// transfers at the call even when the body only READS the param
		// (`Map.findSlot`'s key feeds witness hash/equals calls, never a store).
		// Without this bit a CONCRETE caller doesn't see the transfer and releases
		// the arg too — the callee's `dropTypeParam` plus the caller's release
		// double-drop the key (the String-keyed `m.get("a")` UAF).
		//
		// The signal is the DECLARED parameter type (`maxonParamTypes`), NOT the
		// per-value `isValueTypeParam` table: the table's contents differ between
		// the stdlib cache-warm pipeline and the user pipeline (warm OVER-marked —
		// spurious consume bits on `List.get`/`walkTo`'s receiver released the
		// list out from under `get(1)` on the cached leg only — while the user
		// pipeline never marked at all). The declared type is the same fact on
		// both legs; cache-RESTORED functions have empty `maxonParamTypes`, which
		// is fine — their warm-computed bits arrive via the restored registry and
		// the `alreadyConsumed` skip keeps them.
		if paramIndex < func.maxonParamTypes.count() 'hasDeclaredType'
			let declaredType = try func.maxonParamTypes.get(paramIndex) otherwise panic("analyzeParamConsumes: maxonParamTypes.get({paramIndex}) OOB despite bounds check")
			if maxonTypeIsTypeParameter(declaredType) 'genericParam'
				setConsumeBit(project, funcName: func.name, paramIndex: paramIndex, paramCount: func.paramCount)
				logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-PCA-SET func={func.name} pos={paramIndex} (type-param convention)")
				flipped = true
				continue
			end 'genericParam'
		end 'hasDeclaredType'
		if paramValueReachesConsumeSink(module, func: func, valueId: paramVal, project: project, mayReturnArg: mayReturnArg) 'consumed'
			setConsumeBit(project, funcName: func.name, paramIndex: paramIndex, paramCount: func.paramCount)
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-PCA-SET func={func.name} pos={paramIndex}")
			flipped = true
		end 'consumed'
	end 'eachParam'

	// Transparent-wrapper return-side fact: the function RETURNS a value owning a
	// consumed param's +1 (a `Self{field: arg}` wrapper). Recorded once stable.
	if not project.funcReturnsConsumedArg.contains(func.name) 'notYetWrapper'
		if functionReturnsConsumedArg(module, func: func, paramValues: paramValues, project: project) 'isWrapper'
			project.funcReturnsConsumedArg.insert(func.name)
			flipped = true
		end 'isWrapper'
	end 'notYetWrapper'

	return flipped
end 'updateFuncConsumeBits'

// Sentinel: a parameter index with no `param` op in the body (e.g. an unused param
// the lowerer never materialized) — never a consume candidate.
let CONSUME_NO_VALUE = (-1) as ValueId

// True iff `valueId` (a parameter's SSA value) reaches a CONSUME SINK anywhere in
// `func` — a heap store/box of it, or a call that consumes it at its argument
// position. Post-mem2reg the parameter is a single SSA value used directly at its
// sinks (no slot relays / pointer-identity copies survive — the unary opcodes are
// all arithmetic/float, none of which alias a managed pointer), so a single forward
// scan over the body for a direct sink is exact. A param re-passed to a consuming
// callee is caught as the call-sink (the forwarding edge); a param stored into a
// field/element/wrapper is caught as the store-sink.
function paramValueReachesConsumeSink(module StdModule, func IrFunction, valueId ValueId, project Project, mayReturnArg MayReturnArgMap) returns bool
	// The set of SSA values that ALIAS the parameter: the param's own value, plus the
	// result of any call that MAY-RETURN one of those aliases as its argument (an
	// identity-passthrough whose result is the same pointer). Grown to a fixpoint so a
	// param laundered through a CHAIN of passthroughs (`resolveFileURL` then
	// `normalizeSeparators`) is followed all the way to its store-sink.
	var aliases = ValueIdArray.create()
	aliases.push(valueId)
	var expanded = true
	while expanded 'growAliases'
		expanded = false
		for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
			let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("paramValueReachesConsumeSink: blockRef not in module.blocks")
			for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
				let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("paramValueReachesConsumeSink: opIdx not in module.ops")
				let aliasedResult = callPassesThroughAlias(op, aliases: aliases, mayReturnArg: mayReturnArg)
				if aliasedResult != CONSUME_NO_VALUE and not valueIdArrayContains(aliases, vid: aliasedResult) 'newAlias'
					aliases.push(aliasedResult)
					expanded = true
					logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-PCA-ALIAS func={func.name} param=%{valueId} aliasResult=%{aliasedResult}")
				end 'newAlias'
			end 'eachOp'
		end 'eachBlock'
	end 'growAliases'

	for aliasId in aliases 'eachAlias'
		for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
			let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("paramValueReachesConsumeSink: blockRef not in module.blocks (sink scan)")
			if blockBodyOrTermSinks(module, block: block, valueId: aliasId, project: project) 'sunk'
				return true
			end 'sunk'
		end 'eachBlock'
	end 'eachAlias'
	return false
end 'paramValueReachesConsumeSink'

// If `op` is a call that MAY-RETURN one of its arguments AND that argument is in the
// current `aliases` set, the call's RESULT id (it aliases the same parameter); else
// `CONSUME_NO_VALUE`. The structural basis of the passthrough-aliasing edge: a call to
// `G` returns its arg `j` on some path (`mayReturnArg[G][j]`), so passing a
// param-aliased value at position `j` makes the result another handle on the param.
function callPassesThroughAlias(op StdOp, aliases ValueIdArray, mayReturnArg MayReturnArgMap) returns ValueId
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callResultAliasesArg(c, aliases: aliases, mayReturnArg: mayReturnArg)
		arith gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		control gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		memory gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		system gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'callPassesThroughAlias'

function callResultAliasesArg(c StdCallOp, aliases ValueIdArray, mayReturnArg MayReturnArgMap) returns ValueId
	return match c 'check'
		call(resultId, callee, argIds) gives calleeResultAliasesArg(resultId, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, aliases: aliases, mayReturnArg: mayReturnArg)
		tryCall(resultId, callee, argIds, _) gives calleeResultAliasesArg(resultId, callee: callee, argIds: argIds, aliases: aliases, mayReturnArg: mayReturnArg)
		ret gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
	end 'check'
end 'callResultAliasesArg'

// `resultId` iff `callee` may-return its arg at a position whose argument is currently
// a param-alias; else `CONSUME_NO_VALUE`.
function calleeResultAliasesArg(resultId ValueId, callee String, argIds ValueIdArray, aliases ValueIdArray, mayReturnArg MayReturnArgMap) returns ValueId
	let returnedPositions = try mayReturnArg.get(callee) otherwise return CONSUME_NO_VALUE
	var idx = 0
	while idx < argIds.count() 'each'
		let aid = try argIds.get(idx) otherwise panic("calleeResultAliasesArg: argIds.get OOB despite idx < count")
		if valueIdArrayContains(aliases, vid: aid) and boolArrayGet(returnedPositions, idx: idx) 'aliasReturned'
			return resultId
		end 'aliasReturned'
		idx = idx + 1
	end 'each'
	return CONSUME_NO_VALUE
end 'calleeResultAliasesArg'

// True iff `func` increfs `valueId` anywhere (`stdlib.__mm_incref(valueId)` or its
// bare/`mm_incref` spellings). A function that increfs a param took its OWN reference
// to it (a retain), so storing it afterward is a borrow-capture, not a consume of
// the caller's reference. (The lowered stdlib bodies contain manual increfs only at
// the few retain sites — `lowerCreateCursor` — never at the move-store mutators, so
// this cleanly separates retain from consume.)
function functionIncrefsValue(module StdModule, func IrFunction, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("functionIncrefsValue: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("functionIncrefsValue: opIdx not in module.ops")
			if opIncrefsValue(op, valueId: valueId) 'increfs'
				return true
			end 'increfs'
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return false
end 'functionIncrefsValue'

function opIncrefsValue(op StdOp, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callIncrefsValue(c, valueId: valueId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opIncrefsValue'

function callIncrefsValue(c StdCallOp, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives calleeIsIncref(callee) and valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: valueId)
		tryCall(_, callee, argIds, _) gives calleeIsIncref(callee) and valueIdArrayContains(argIds, vid: valueId)
		ret gives false
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callIncrefsValue'

function calleeIsIncref(callee String) returns bool
	return callee == "stdlib.__mm_incref" or callee == "__mm_incref" or callee == "mm_incref"
end 'calleeIsIncref'

// Scan one block's body ops + terminator for a consume sink of `valueId`.
function blockBodyOrTermSinks(module StdModule, block IrBlock, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
		let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("blockBodyOrTermSinks: opIdx not in module.ops")
		if opIsConsumeSinkFor(op, valueId: valueId, project: project) 'sink'
			return true
		end 'sink'
	end 'eachOp'
	if block.hasTerminatorOp() 'hasTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("blockBodyOrTermSinks: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		if opIsConsumeSinkFor(term, valueId: valueId, project: project) 'termSink'
			return true
		end 'termSink'
	end 'hasTerm'
	return false
end 'blockBodyOrTermSinks'

// True iff `op` is a DIRECT consume sink of `valueId`:
//   - a `store_indirect` / `box_value` whose STORED value is `valueId` (moved into
//     heap storage), OR
//   - a call that CONSUMES `valueId` at its argument position (an intrinsic leaf or a
//     module function whose consume bit for that position is already set).
function opIsConsumeSinkFor(op StdOp, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	if opStoresValueIntoHeap(op, valueId: valueId) 'store'
		return true
	end 'store'
	return callConsumesArgValue(op, valueId: valueId, project: project)
end 'opIsConsumeSinkFor'

// True iff `op` stores `valueId` AS THE STORED VALUE into heap memory
// (`store_indirect`'s value operand or `box_value`'s value operand). Storing it as
// an ADDRESS/base is not a consume (the pointer is read, not the pointee moved).
function opStoresValueIntoHeap(op StdOp, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		system(s) gives sysStoresValue(s, valueId: valueId)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		call gives false
		memory gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'opStoresValueIntoHeap'

function sysStoresValue(s StdSystemOp, valueId ValueId) returns bool
	return match s 'check'
		storeIndirect(_, _, storedId, _, _) gives storedId == valueId
		boxValue(_, storedId, _) gives storedId == valueId
		globalAddr to loadByte gives false
		osExit to loadFramePtr gives false
		loadIndirect gives false
		funcAddr gives false
		drop gives false
		osAllocPages to osDirMkdir gives false
		atomicInc to osLockRelease gives false
		unboxValue gives false
		loadLayoutDescriptor to dropTypeParam gives false
	end 'check'
end 'sysStoresValue'

// True iff `op` is a call passing `valueId` at an argument position the callee
// CONSUMES (per the fixpoint's current bits / the intrinsic leaf set).
function callConsumesArgValue(op StdOp, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	return match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives callConsumesValueArg(c, valueId: valueId, project: project)
		arith gives false
		control gives false
		memory gives false
		system gives false
	end 'dispatch'
end 'callConsumesArgValue'

function callConsumesValueArg(c StdCallOp, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	return match c 'check'
		call(_, callee, argIds) gives calleeConsumesArgAt(callee, argIds: argIds, valueId: valueId, project: project)
		tryCall(_, callee, argIds, _) gives calleeConsumesArgAt(callee, argIds: argIds, valueId: valueId, project: project)
		ret gives false
		indirectCall to errorReturn gives false
	end 'check'
end 'callConsumesValueArg'

// True iff `callee` consumes the argument equal to `valueId` (found at its position
// in `argIds`). An intrinsic leaf-consumer consumes its value arg (the LAST arg);
// otherwise consult the callee's current consume bits for that position.
function calleeConsumesArgAt(callee String, argIds ValueIdArray, valueId ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	var idx = 0
	while idx < argIds.count() 'each'
		let aid = try argIds.get(idx) otherwise panic("calleeConsumesArgAt: argIds.get OOB despite idx < count")
		if aid == valueId 'atPos'
			if calleeConsumesParamIndex(callee, paramIndex: idx, project: project) 'consumes'
				return true
			end 'consumes'
		end 'atPos'
		idx = idx + 1
	end 'each'
	return false
end 'calleeConsumesArgAt'

// True iff a call to `callee` consumes its parameter at `paramIndex`. Reads the
// consume registry — which `seedIntrinsicLeafConsumers` pre-populated for the
// runtime.std raw helpers and the fixpoint fills in for every analyzable callee — so
// intrinsic leaves and module functions are looked up through ONE table.
module function calleeConsumesParamIndex(callee String, paramIndex NodeIndex, project Project) returns bool
	let bits = try project.funcParamConsumes.get(callee) otherwise return false
	return boolArrayGet(bits, idx: paramIndex)
end 'calleeConsumesParamIndex'

// ============================================================
// Transparent-wrapper return-side fact (`funcReturnsConsumedArg`)
// ============================================================

// True iff `func` is a TRANSPARENT-WRAPPER reinterpret: every return terminator
// returns a CONSUMED PARAMETER DIRECTLY (the result IS the param's pointer, no fresh
// wrapping allocation between). This is the `BuiltinArrayLiteral` shape — `Array.init`
// /`Vector.init`'s `return Self{managed: managed}` over a single-pointer-field struct
// lowers to "return the managed param" (a no-op reinterpret). The result carries the
// SAME +1 as the param, so a caller's global-store of it needs no separate
// store-incref (`isTransparentWrapResult`).
//
// CRUCIALLY this EXCLUDES a real multi-field constructor (`String.init`'s
// `String{managed, isAsciiFlag}`): that ALLOCATES a fresh struct and stores `managed`
// into a field — the result is a DISTINCT object that takes its OWN +1 on `managed`
// via the inserter's field-store incref, so the caller's arg decref is still needed.
// A real constructor's return value is alloc-defined (not the param itself), so the
// "returns the param directly" test below rejects it. (The earlier alloc-based test
// had this backwards — it matched the real constructors and missed the reinterprets.)
function functionReturnsConsumedArg(module StdModule, func IrFunction, paramValues ParamValueMap, project Project) returns bool
	var sawReturn = false
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("functionReturnsConsumedArg: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("functionReturnsConsumedArg: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		let retVal = consumeReturnValueOf(term)
		if retVal == CONSUME_NO_VALUE 'notReturn'
			continue
		end 'notReturn'
		sawReturn = true
		if not returnedValueIsConsumedParam(func, paramValues: paramValues, retVal: retVal, project: project) 'notReinterpret'
			return false
		end 'notReinterpret'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return sawReturn
end 'functionReturnsConsumedArg'

// True iff `retVal` IS a consumed parameter of `func` returned directly (the
// transparent reinterpret). The returned SSA value equals a param whose consume bit is
// set — no fresh allocation wraps it. A real constructor returns an alloc result (a
// different SSA id than any param), so it fails this test.
function returnedValueIsConsumedParam(func IrFunction, paramValues ParamValueMap, retVal ValueId, project Project) returns bool
	for paramIndex in 0 upto func.paramCount 'eachParam'
		let pv = paramValueForIndex(paramValues, paramIndex: paramIndex)
		if pv == CONSUME_NO_VALUE 'noVal'
			continue
		end 'noVal'
		if pv == retVal and calleeConsumesParamIndex(func.name, paramIndex: paramIndex, project: project) 'isReinterpret'
			return true
		end 'isReinterpret'
	end 'eachParam'
	return false
end 'returnedValueIsConsumedParam'

// The returned ValueId of a `ret`/`errorReturn` terminator, else `CONSUME_NO_VALUE`.
function consumeReturnValueOf(term StdOp) returns ValueId
	return match term 'dispatch'
		call(c) gives consumeReturnValueOfCall(c)
		arith gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		control gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		memory gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		system gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
	end 'dispatch'
end 'consumeReturnValueOf'

function consumeReturnValueOfCall(c StdCallOp) returns ValueId
	return match c 'check'
		ret(retValId) gives retValId
		call to tailCall gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		param gives CONSUME_NO_VALUE
		errorReturn(retValId, _) gives retValId
	end 'check'
end 'consumeReturnValueOfCall'

// ============================================================
// Intrinsic leaf-consumers (the runtime.std raw helpers)
// ============================================================

// Seed the consume registry for the runtime.std raw helpers whose bodies are NOT in
// this module (slot-form, linked at the backend) and so cannot be analyzed. Each
// MOVES its managed value argument into a container WITHOUT increfing; the
// container's destructor performs the matching decref. The moved value is the LAST
// argument in every such helper (the receiver/index/target args precede it). These
// are compiler-internal primitives (a closed set), not user API. (`__managed_mem_set`
// IS analyzable Maxon — it raw-stores via `__Internals.storeIndirect` — so the
// structural store-sink rule detects it without a seed; it is intentionally NOT
// listed here.)
function seedIntrinsicLeafConsumers(project Project)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_insert_last_value", paramCount: 2)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_insert_first_value", paramCount: 2)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_insert_after_value", paramCount: 3)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_insert_before_value", paramCount: 3)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_node_set_value", paramCount: 2)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_push_value", paramCount: 2)
	seedLastArgConsumer(project, callee: "mrt_managed_list_alloc_node", paramCount: 1)
end 'seedIntrinsicLeafConsumers'

// Record `callee` as consuming its LAST parameter (the moved value position).
function seedLastArgConsumer(project Project, callee String, paramCount NodeIndex)
	setConsumeBit(project, funcName: callee, paramIndex: paramCount - 1, paramCount: paramCount)
end 'seedLastArgConsumer'

// ============================================================
// Registry mutation + param/value plumbing
// ============================================================

// Set `funcName`'s consume bit for `paramIndex`, growing the BoolArray to
// `paramCount` entries (default false) on first touch.
function setConsumeBit(project Project, funcName String, paramIndex NodeIndex, paramCount NodeIndex)
	var bits = try project.funcParamConsumes.get(funcName) otherwise growConsumeBits(paramCount)
	while bits.count() <= paramIndex 'grow'
		bits.push(false)
	end 'grow'
	try bits.set(paramIndex, value: true) otherwise panic("setConsumeBit: set OOB after grow")
	project.funcParamConsumes.upsert(funcName, value: bits)
end 'setConsumeBit'

function growConsumeBits(paramCount NodeIndex) returns BoolArray
	var bits = BoolArray.create()
	var i = 0
	while i < paramCount 'fill'
		bits.push(false)
		i = i + 1
	end 'fill'
	return bits
end 'growConsumeBits'

function boolArrayGet(bits BoolArray, idx NodeIndex) returns bool
	return try bits.get(idx) otherwise false
end 'boolArrayGet'

// Render a BoolArray as `[1,0,1]` for trace logging.
function boolArrayToString(bits BoolArray) returns String
	var out = "["
	var i = 0
	while i < bits.count() 'each'
		if i > 0 'sep'
			out = "{out},"
		end 'sep'
		let v = try bits.get(i) otherwise false
		out = (("{out}1") if v else ("{out}0"))
		i = i + 1
	end 'each'
	return "{out}]"
end 'boolArrayToString'

// Per-callee map from a function name to a BoolArray flagging which parameter
// positions that function MAY RETURN on some path (the identity-passthrough relation).
// Built ONCE up front by `computeMayReturnArgMap` and consulted by the consume walk's
// passthrough-aliasing edge (`calleeResultAliasesArg`).
typealias MayReturnArgMap = Map with (String, BoolArray)

// Build the may-return-arg relation for every function in `module`: a position is
// flagged iff SOME `ret`/`errorReturn` terminator returns that parameter's SSA value
// DIRECTLY (`return param` — the no-transform passthrough branch). A return value that
// is an allocation / arith / a different SSA id is not a passthrough and sets no bit.
// (Direct param-equality is sufficient for the passthrough shapes that matter —
// `resolveFileURL`/`normalizeSeparators`'s `return input`/`return path`; the value
// survives mem2reg as the param's own SSA id with no intervening pointer-identity copy,
// per the same single-SSA-value reasoning the consume sink scan relies on.)
function computeMayReturnArgMap(module StdModule) returns MayReturnArgMap
	var out = MayReturnArgMap.create()
	for funcIdx in 0 upto module.functions.count() 'eachFunc'
		let func = try module.functions.get(funcIdx) otherwise panic("computeMayReturnArgMap: functions.get OOB at {funcIdx}")
		if func.blockRefs.count() == 0 'empty'
			continue
		end 'empty'
		let positions = computeReturnedParamPositions(module, func: func)
		if positions.present 'hasReturnedParam'
			out.upsert(func.name, value: positions.bits)
			logTrace(LogCategory.ir, message: function() gives "RC-MAYRETARG func={func.name} positions={boolArrayToString(positions.bits)}")
		end 'hasReturnedParam'
	end 'eachFunc'
	return out
end 'computeMayReturnArgMap'

// A BoolArray of returned-parameter positions plus a presence flag (true iff at least
// one position is returned) — the per-function result of the may-return-arg scan.
type ReturnedParamPositions
	export var present as bool
	export var bits as BoolArray

	export static function none() returns ReturnedParamPositions
		return Self{present: false, bits: BoolArray.create()}
	end 'none'

	export static function some(bits BoolArray) returns ReturnedParamPositions
		return Self{present: true, bits: bits}
	end 'some'
end 'ReturnedParamPositions'

function computeReturnedParamPositions(module StdModule, func IrFunction) returns ReturnedParamPositions
	let paramValues = collectParamValues(module, func: func)
	var bits = BoolArray.create()
	var i = 0
	while i < func.paramCount 'fillFalse'
		bits.push(false)
		i = i + 1
	end 'fillFalse'
	var any = false
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("computeReturnedParamPositions: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		if not block.hasTerminatorOp() 'noTerm'
			continue
		end 'noTerm'
		let term = try module.ops.get(block.terminatorIndex()) otherwise panic("computeReturnedParamPositions: terminatorIndex not in module.ops")
		let retVal = consumeReturnValueOf(term)
		if retVal == CONSUME_NO_VALUE 'notReturn'
			continue
		end 'notReturn'
		for paramIndex in 0 upto func.paramCount 'eachParam'
			let pv = paramValueForIndex(paramValues, paramIndex: paramIndex)
			if pv != CONSUME_NO_VALUE and pv == retVal 'returnsThisParam'
				try bits.set(paramIndex, value: true) otherwise panic("computeReturnedParamPositions: bits.set OOB at {paramIndex}")
				any = true
			end 'returnsThisParam'
		end 'eachParam'
	end 'eachBlock'
	if not any 'noneReturned'
		return ReturnedParamPositions.none()
	end 'noneReturned'
	return ReturnedParamPositions.some(bits)
end 'computeReturnedParamPositions'

// Per-function map from a parameter ABI index to the SSA value its `param` op
// defines (the body's handle on that parameter). Built once per function.
typealias ParamValueMap = Map with (NodeIndex, ValueId)

function collectParamValues(module StdModule, func IrFunction) returns ParamValueMap
	var pv = ParamValueMap.create()
	for blockRef in func.blockRefs 'eachBlock'
		let block = try module.blocks.get(blockRef) otherwise panic("collectParamValues: blockRef not in module.blocks")
		for opIdx in block.opRefs 'eachOp'
			let op = try module.ops.get(opIdx) otherwise panic("collectParamValues: opIdx not in module.ops")
			recordParamOp(op, pv: pv)
		end 'eachOp'
	end 'eachBlock'
	return pv
end 'collectParamValues'

function recordParamOp(op StdOp, pv ParamValueMap)
	match op 'dispatch'
		call(c) then recordParamCall(c, pv: pv)
		arith then break 'dispatch'
		control then break 'dispatch'
		memory then break 'dispatch'
		system then break 'dispatch'
	end 'dispatch'
end 'recordParamOp'

function recordParamCall(c StdCallOp, pv ParamValueMap)
	match c 'check'
		param(resultId, paramIndex, _) then pv.upsert(paramIndex as NodeIndex, value: resultId)
		ret then break 'check'
		call to tailCall then break 'check'
		errorReturn then break 'check'
	end 'check'
end 'recordParamCall'

function paramValueForIndex(pv ParamValueMap, paramIndex NodeIndex) returns ValueId
	return try pv.get(paramIndex) otherwise CONSUME_NO_VALUE
end 'paramValueForIndex'
